<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>It was his first meeting of the season and the 31-year-oldhe did the double in the 200m and 400m events in front of a near capacity crowd.Makwala, who is based in his native country, ran one of the fastest times in the 400m when he clocked 45.06 seconds to bag his first win of the season. But he finished fifth in the men’s 200m when he managed 20.89 seconds.Mzansi’s prominent sprinter Anaso Jobodwana won the men’s 200m when he stopped the clock in 20.13 seconds, with promising sprinter Clarence Munyai grabbing second place with 20.18 seconds.Makwala will run the 300m in the second leg in Tshwane at the Tuks Athletics Stadium on Thursday. Athletics SA, together with their partners Telecom and Stillwater Agency, put together a world-class event according to Makwala, who has travelled all over the world to take part in high-profile events. Makwala has participated in huge one-day series events with big prize money on offer but he praised the Grand Prix Series. Makwala said: “This is the best meeting so far in Africa. I think the atmosphere is awesome.” Makwala, who is not shy to share his opinion, said South Africa could stage big athletics event. Makwala said: “Yeah, the IAAF World Championships could be hosted here. SA has world-class facilities to host top-class events. They should go for it.”I’ll run the 300m in Pretoria. I’m excited to be in SA.”Makwala will stay in SA until the duration of the Grand Prix. The final leg takes place in Paarl, near Cape Town, on 22 March.  Like this story? Get the free Daily Kick App today and stay on top of your game with only the best from SunSport, Soccer Laduma, KickOff and many more!ALL YOUR SOCCER AND NEWS IN ONE PLACE THATHA ZONKE